 fences and mention the updated progress file. It’s important to point out the current exports from `index.ts` like `StorageData`, `isAccountAvailable`, and others that haven’t been exported. I should also highlight that `formatResetAt` is only used by the status command for UI formatting. I’ll craft clear patch suggestions without line numbers but by referencing section headings, possibly combining suggestions and exact replacements while being thorough.\"}]}"},{"type":"text","text":"Reviewed against:\n\n- `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/spec.md`\n- `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context.md`\n- `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/progress.md`\n- `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context/restructure-scope-and-target-architecture.md`\n- `AGENTS.md`\n- `README.md`\n- `index.ts`\n- `index.test.ts`\n\nI also updated `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/progress.md` with a review note.\n\n## Verdict\n\nThe spec is strong directionally, but it is **not implementation-ready yet**. It has **3 critical mismatches** with the current code/task context, plus a few scope-expanding ambiguities that would likely cause overbuilding.\n\n---\n\n## 1) Critical issues\n\n### 1. The spec treats refresh deduplication as current parity, but the code does not do that\nIn `index.ts`, `ensureValidToken()` refreshes directly; there is **no per-account in-flight refresh dedupe** today.\n\nSo this spec bullet is incorrect as a parity claim:\n\n- `Refreshes must be deduplicated per account...`\n\nThat is a valid improvement, but it is **not current behavior**, so putting it in the “Behavior parity contract” silently expands scope.\n\n**Risk:** implementer may believe they are preserving behavior when they are actually introducing new concurrency semantics.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Task docs disagree on whether a non-pi consumer is required\n`spec.md` says:\n\n- optional gateway layer\n- Phase 4 is optional\n- non-pi consumer is not required\n\nBut `context/restructure-scope-and-target-architecture.md` says Definition of done includes:\n\n- `at least one non-pi consumer (gateway or CLI) runs against the same core`\n- `minimal migration notes added to README`\n\nThese are materially different acceptance criteria.\n\n**Risk:** one implementer stops after internal extraction; another thinks a gateway/CLI + README update is required.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Public API compatibility is overstated and inaccurate versus current exports\nCurrent root exports from `index.ts` are:\n\n- `Account`\n- `CodexUsageSnapshot`\n- `ProviderModelDef`\n- `getOpenAICodexMirror`\n- `parseCodexUsageResponse`\n- `isUsageUntouched`\n- `getNextResetAt`\n- `getWeeklyResetAt`\n- `pickBestAccount`\n- `AccountManager`\n- `buildMulticodexProviderConfig`\n- default export\n- `createStreamWrapper`\n- `isQuotaErrorMessage`\n\nBut the spec says to keep/stabilize names like:\n\n- `StorageData`\n- `StorageAdapter`\n- `UsageClient`\n- `TokenRefresher`\n- `createAccountManager`\n- `isAccountAvailable`\n- `getMaxUsedPercent`\n- `onStateChange(...)`\n- `removeAccount(...)`\n\nSeveral of those do **not exist today** or are not exported.\n\n**Risk:** the spec accidentally creates a much larger public API commitment than the codebase or README currently support.\n\n---\n\n## 2) Important improvements\n\n### 1. Narrow storage migration scope to what is actually proven today\nCurrent code uses one concrete file:\n\n- `~/.pi/agent/multicodex.json`\n\nwith a simple shape:\n\n- `{ accounts, activeEmail? }`\n\nThe spec currently requires reading legacy files from both the monolith and the reference implementation, plus salvage of partially corrupt files.\n\nThat may be reasonable later, but it is not grounded in current tests or current shipped behavior.\n\n**Recommendation:** make reference-implementation migration and corrupt-file salvage **optional unless backed by fixtures/tests added in this task**.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Clarify that `multicodex-core` / `multicodex-pi-adapter` are logical module boundaries, not necessarily separate packages\nThe spec names them like packages, while the non-goals say no broad package/workspace restructure.\n\n**Recommendation:** explicitly state first pass is **module split inside the existing package**, with root `index.ts` preserved as the compatibility barrel/default extension entrypoint.\n\n---\n\n### 3. `formatResetAt` should not be described as core-owned\nIn current code, `formatResetAt()` is presentation formatting used by status UI. That is adapter/UI territory, not platform-agnostic core.\n\n**Recommendation:** keep timestamp math in core, keep human-readable formatting in adapter status/presentation code.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Add explicit acceptance criteria for the current bounded rotation behavior\nCurrent code has:\n\n- `MAX_ROTATION_RETRIES = 5`\n\nThe spec says retry remains bounded, but does not say whether parity means keeping the current bound.\n\n**Recommendation:** either preserve `5` explicitly or explicitly allow changing it with tests/docs.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Add an adapter test for provider-unavailable startup behavior\nThe spec requires:\n\n- warn/skip registration if pi provider unavailable\n\nCurrent tests do not appear to lock that in. It should be explicit in adapter test coverage.\n\n---\n\n## 3) Nice-to-haves\n\n### 1. Explicitly say manual account override remains session-local\nThe spec hints this in risks, but making it a direct constraint would reduce ambiguity.\n\nCurrent code:\n- `manualEmail` is in-memory only\n- it is not persisted to storage\n\n---\n\n### 2. Add README update as a small required deliverable\nNot a full doc rewrite; just enough to explain:\n- internal core/adapter split\n- current install path unchanged\n- current commands unchanged\n\nThis would reconcile the context doc’s README note with the spec.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Define the minimum non-pi validation artifact\nIf non-pi reuse is required at all, say what counts:\n- unit test harness\n- tiny CLI smoke script\n- gateway stub\n- integration test fixture\n\nThat avoids overbuilding a real service.\n\n---\n\n## 4) Concrete patch suggestions (exact text edits)\n\nBelow are targeted edits to `spec.md` only.\n\n---\n\n### Patch 1 — fix command-name ambiguity with context doc\n\n**Replace this block:**\n```md\n- The current README exposes a very small public surface:\n  - `/multicodex-login`\n  - `/multicodex-use`\n  - `/multicodex-status`\n  - local dev install via `pi -e ./index.ts`\n```\n\n**With:**\n```md\n- The current README exposes a very small public surface:\n  - `/multicodex-login`\n  - `/multicodex-use`\n  - `/multicodex-status`\n  - local dev install via `pi -e ./index.ts`\n- For this task, `/multicodex-use` is the canonical existing manual-switch command. Any rename such as `/multicodex-switch` is out of scope unless README, tests, and compatibility behavior are updated together.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 2 — stop describing refresh dedupe as existing parity\n\n**Replace this block:**\n```md\n### 3) Token refresh\n\n- Tokens are considered valid if they have at least 5 minutes of remaining life.\n- Expired tokens must be refreshed before use.\n- Refreshes must be deduplicated per account so concurrent callers do not trigger multiple refreshes for the same refresh token.\n- Successful refresh persists updated credentials back to managed storage.\n```\n\n**With:**\n```md\n### 3) Token refresh\n\n- Tokens are considered valid if they have at least 5 minutes of remaining life.\n- Expired tokens must be refreshed before use.\n- Successful refresh persists updated credentials back to managed storage.\n- Per-account refresh deduplication is a valid improvement for this task, but it is not part of the current monolith's proven behavior contract. If added, it must be treated as an intentional enhancement with dedicated tests.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 3 — make the first-pass architecture explicitly module-based, not package-mandatory\n\n**Insert after this sentence in `## Non-goals`:**\n```md\n- No broad package/workspace restructuring unless required to keep the core importable; the first pass should prefer module boundaries over repo re-layout.\n```\n\n**Insert this new bullet immediately after it:**\n```md\n- In this first pass, `multicodex-core` and `multicodex-pi-adapter` refer to logical module boundaries inside the existing package unless a stronger packaging split is required by tests or distribution constraints.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 4 — narrow public API compatibility to actual current exports\n\n**Replace everything from `### Core exports` through the end of `### Core methods / behavior surface` with:**\n```md\n### Root compatibility exports\n\nThe root `index.ts` compatibility barrel must continue to export the names that are exported today and used by the current tests:\n\n- `Account`\n- `AccountManager`\n- `CodexUsageSnapshot`\n- `ProviderModelDef`\n- `buildMulticodexProviderConfig`\n- `createStreamWrapper`\n- `getNextResetAt`\n- `getOpenAICodexMirror`\n- `getWeeklyResetAt`\n- `isQuotaErrorMessage`\n- `isUsageUntouched`\n- `parseCodexUsageResponse`\n- `pickBestAccount`\n- default export: the pi extension function\n\nNew core-only interfaces such as `StorageAdapter`, `UsageClient`, `TokenRefresher`, `StorageData`, or `createAccountManager` may be introduced, but they are not required to be root-stable in this task unless tests and docs are updated to make them public.\n\n### Core behavior surface required for adapter parity\n\nIf `AccountManager` remains a class, it must support the methods the current adapter behavior depends on:\n\n- `getAccounts()`\n- `getAccount(email)`\n- `getActiveAccount()`\n- `getManualAccount()`\n- `hasManualAccount()`\n- `getAvailableManualAccount(options?)`\n- `setActiveAccount(email)`\n- `setManualAccount(email)`\n- `clearManualAccount()`\n- `addOrUpdateAccount(email, creds)`\n- `getCachedUsage(email)`\n- `refreshUsageForAccount(account, options?)`\n- `refreshUsageForAllAccounts(options?)`\n- `refreshUsageIfStale(accounts, options?)`\n- `activateBestAccount(options?)`\n- `ensureValidToken(account)`\n- `handleQuotaExceeded(account, options?)`\n\nWarning and diagnostics behavior may remain an injected callback or small logger surface rather than requiring a broader `onStateChange(...)` API in this task.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 5 — narrow migration scope to current proven storage contract\n\n**Replace this block:**\n```md\n### Migration behavior\n\n- Treat storage migration as **additive and idempotent**.\n- Read legacy files from the current repo version and the reference implementation as needed.\n- Accept and normalize:\n  - the current monolith’s legacy unversioned storage format\n  - the reference implementation’s versioned storage format\n  - partially corrupt files that still contain salvageable account entries\n- On successful load of a legacy file, write back the canonical versioned format.\n- Preserve unknown-but-harmless data only if it is explicitly needed; otherwise normalize to the stable schema.\n- Do not persist adapter-only ephemeral state such as manual session overrides or pi-auth-only runtime accounts.\n```\n\n**With:**\n```md\n### Migration behavior\n\n- Treat storage migration as **additive and idempotent**.\n- Required compatibility input for this task is the current monolith's file at `~/.pi/agent/multicodex.json` with the legacy unversioned shape `{ accounts, activeEmail? }`.\n- The pi adapter owns the default file path; the core must receive storage through an injected adapter and must not hard-code the pi path.\n- Support for additional legacy shapes from the reference implementation is optional unless this task adds explicit fixtures and regression tests for them.\n- Corrupt-file salvage is optional scope; if implemented, the spec/tests must define exactly which fields are salvageable and what happens to malformed records.\n- On successful load of a supported legacy file, write back the canonical versioned format.\n- Do not persist adapter-only ephemeral state such as manual session overrides or other runtime-only session state.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 6 — keep formatting out of core\n\n**Replace this row in the module extraction table:**\n```md\n| `normalizeUsedPercent`, `normalizeResetAt`, `parseUsageWindow`, `parseCodexUsageResponse`, `isUsageUntouched`, `getNextResetAt`, `getWeeklyResetAt`, `formatResetAt` | `core/usage.ts` | `formatResetAt` may also be surfaced by the adapter UI layer, but the math should live in core. |\n```\n\n**With:**\n```md\n| `normalizeUsedPercent`, `normalizeResetAt`, `parseUsageWindow`, `parseCodexUsageResponse`, `isUsageUntouched`, `getNextResetAt`, `getWeeklyResetAt` | `core/usage.ts` | Keep usage normalization and reset selection pure and platform-agnostic. |\n| `formatResetAt` | `adapter/pi/status.ts` (or adapter-local formatting module) | Human-readable status formatting is presentation logic and should stay out of core. |\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 7 — reconcile optional gateway with required non-pi validation\n\n**Replace this block:**\n```md\n### Phase 4 — optional non-pi consumer spike\n\n- If time permits, add a tiny gateway or CLI proof-of-use against the core.\n- This is a validation milestone, not a prerequisite for the core/adapter split.\n```\n\n**With:**\n```md\n### Phase 4 — non-pi validation\n\n- Add at least one non-pi validation path that exercises the core without `@mariozechner/pi-coding-agent` imports.\n- This validation may be a small test harness, CLI smoke script, or gateway spike.\n- Shipping a productized gateway/service is optional; proving the core is reusable outside pi is required.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 8 — tighten definition of done to match code + context\n\n**Replace this block:**\n```md\n## Definition of done\n\n- The monolith has been split into a reusable core boundary and a pi-specific adapter boundary.\n- Core logic no longer imports pi runtime APIs.\n- Existing pi commands and provider behavior remain functionally equivalent to the current documented behavior.\n- Legacy storage loads successfully and migrates to the canonical versioned schema without data loss for valid accounts.\n- Retry/rotation and usage-cache behavior are covered by regression tests.\n- Current root exports continue to work during the migration window.\n- `npm run lint`, `npm run tsgo`, and `npm run test` all pass.\n- The refactor leaves a clear path for a non-pi consumer to reuse the same core without copying the selection/refresh logic.\n```\n\n**With:**\n```md\n## Definition of done\n\n- The monolith has been split into a reusable core boundary and a pi-specific adapter boundary inside the existing package structure.\n- Core logic no longer imports pi runtime APIs.\n- Existing pi commands and provider behavior remain functionally equivalent to the current documented behavior in `README.md`, including `/multicodex-login`, `/multicodex-use`, and `/multicodex-status`.\n- The bounded usage retry policy remains equivalent to the current code (`2` retries with approximately `300ms` then `900ms` backoff) unless tests/docs are updated together.\n- The bounded stream-rotation policy remains equivalent to the current code (maximum `5` rotation retries) unless tests/docs are updated together.\n- Legacy storage from the current monolith loads successfully and migrates to the canonical versioned schema without data loss for valid accounts.\n- Retry/rotation, usage-cache behavior, and root compatibility exports are covered by regression tests.\n- The repo includes one non-pi validation path that exercises the core without pi runtime imports.\n- `README.md` includes minimal migration notes confirming the internal core/adapter split and that the existing pi install/command surface is unchanged.\n- `npm run lint`, `npm run tsgo`, and `npm run test` all pass.\n```\n\n---\n\n### Patch 9 — add missing adapter test coverage\n\n**In `### Adapter tests`, add these bullets:**\n```md\n- extension startup skips provider registration and warns when `openai-codex-responses` is unavailable\n- root compatibility barrel still exposes the current exported names used by `index.test.ts`\n```\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can next turn this into either:\n\n1. a **clean revised `spec.md` draft**, or  \n2. a **line-by-line review artifact** you can paste into the task folder.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_04c81ebd48e02dfc0169de0429a75c8199be13da0d0d63f79e\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":153,"output":3800,"cacheRead":48000,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":51953,"cost":{"input":0.00038250000000000003,"output":0.057,"cacheRead":0.012,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0693825}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1776157724265,"responseId":"resp_04c81ebd48e02dfc0169de041cec50819993423cc1fdad33b8"},"toolResults":[]}
{"type":"agent_end","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Task: Review `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/spec.md` for technical completeness, correctness against current codebase, ambiguity, missing acceptance criteria, and implementation risk. Validate alignment with `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context.md`, `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/progress.md`, `.agents/tasks/refactor-agnostic/context/restructure-scope-and-target-architecture.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `README.md`, `index.ts`, and `index.test.ts`. Provide: (1) critical issues, (2) important improvements, (3) nice-to-haves, and (4) concrete patch suggestions (exact text edits) to make the spec implementation-ready."}],"timestamp":1776157367814},{"role":"custom","customType":"pi-memory-md","content":"# Project Memory\n\n# Project Memory\n\nAvailable memory files (use memory_read to view full content):\n\n- core/project/archival-memory-shipped.md\n  Description: Archival memory tier shipped with project-scoped SQLite storage, additive archival tools, and verified regression coverage.\n  Tags: project, release, archival-memory, sqlite, tools\n\n- core/project/commits.md\n  Description: Rolling summary of important project commits for pi-memory-md\n  Tags: git, commits, project-id:pi-memory-md\n\n- core/project/home-lab-portainer-vm-docker-access.md\n  Description: Attempt log for retrieving Docker containers from Portainer VM via SSH and qm guest exec\n  Tags: home-lab, proxmox, portainer, docker, troubleshooting, vm-access\n\n- core/project/intent.md\n  Description: Project goal and intent for modifying pi-memory-md\n  Tags: project, intent, goals\n\n- core/project/letta-memfs-architecture/context-index.md\n  Description: Context index and related context document map for the letta-memfs-architecture task\n  Tags: project-id:pi-memory-md, task-id:letta-memfs-architecture, letta-memfs-architecture, context\n\n- core/project/letta-memfs-architecture/progress.md\n  Description: Progress snapshot for letta-memfs-architecture including completed M6 and M7 history/ref-read internals\n  Tags: project-id:pi-memory-md, task-id:letta-memfs-architecture, progress, m6, m7, migration, health, history, testing\n\n- core/project/letta-recall-architecture-task-scaffold.md\n  Description: Scaffolded the new letta-recall-architecture task with context, spec, plan, stage docs, and moved review artifacts into context index\n  Tags: project-id:pi-memory-md, task-id:letta-recall-architecture, letta, recall-memory, tasks, planning\n\n- core/project/low-priority-followup-task-order.md\n  Description: Documented the low-priority follow-up tasks created after recall memory shipped, including recommended execution order and dependency guidance.\n  Tags: project, roadmap, follow-up, priority-low, task-ordering\n\n- core/project/low-priority-followups-completed.md\n  Description: Completed the low-priority follow-up task sequence after recall-memory shipped, including validation outcomes and execution order.\n  Tags: project, roadmap, follow-up, priority-low, completed\n\n- core/project/memory-architecture.md\n  Description: How pi-memory-md memory architecture is organized and intended to function\n  Tags: memory, architecture, pi-memory-md, graph, injection\n\n- core/project/next-high-level-task-after-letta-memfs.md\n  Description: Recommended next high-level task after completing letta-memfs architecture: add Letta-style recall memory, then archival memory\n  Tags: project-id:pi-memory-md, letta, roadmap, next-steps, recall-memory, archival-memory\n\n- core/project/personal-agent-pkm-vision.md\n  Description: Vision note describing pi-memory-md as a broader personal knowledge system for agents, centered on a vault-native knowledge graph for projects, ideas, notes, and session-derived knowledge.\n  Tags: project, vision, architecture, pkm, agents, knowledge-graph, tags\n\n- core/project/pi-subagents-context-progress-frontmatter-conventions.md\n  Description: Relocated: pi-subagents memory now stored under core/project/pi-subagents/\n  Tags: pi-subagents, relocation\n\n- core/project/pi-subagents-task-scaffold-and-agent-task-inference.md\n  Description: Relocated to pi-subagents folder\n  Tags: pi-subagents, relocation\n\n- core/project/pi-subagents-taskid-routing.md\n  Description: Relocated to pi-subagents folder\n  Tags: pi-subagents, relocation\n\n- core/project/pi-subagents/context-progress-frontmatter-conventions.md\n  Description: pi-subagents task doc conventions: context/progress index files with required frontmatter and validation\n  Tags: pi-subagents, task-files, frontmatter, documentation, testing\n\n- core/project/pi-subagents/task-scaffold-and-agent-task-inference.md\n  Description: Extended pi-subagents with single-agent task dir inference and create-task chain scaffolding\n  Tags: pi-subagents, task-routing, chain, testing\n\n- core/project/pi-subagents/taskid-routing.md\n  Description: Implemented taskId-based chain artifact routing in pi-subagents with sync/async parity\n  Tags: pi-subagents, chain, task-id, artifacts, testing\n\n- core/project/pkm-architecture-progress-2026-03-24.md\n  Description: Summary of PKM frontmatter schema v1 implementation and folder conventions design.\n  Tags: pi-memory-md, pkm, architecture, frontmatter, folder-conventions, progress\n\n- core/project/pkm-architecture-refinement-progress-2026-03-24.md\n  Description: Progress snapshot for PKM architecture realignment decisions including durable object types, inbox/provenance model, and scoring strategy.\n  Tags: project, progress, pkm, architecture, inbox, provenance, agent-memory\n\n- core/project/recall-memory-noise-purged.md\n  Description: Documented cleanup of historical noisy recall rows from the local pi-memory-md recall SQLite database.\n  Tags: project, maintenance, recall-memory, sqlite, cleanup\n\n- core/project/recall-memory-shipped.md\n  Description: Recall memory tier shipped with SQLite-backed storage, additive recall tools, and verified live smoke tests.\n  Tags: project, release, recall-memory, sqlite, tools\n\n- core/project/schema-based-architecture.md\n  Description: Schema-based architecture using single source of truth for directory structure and validation\n  Tags: architecture, schemas, zod, refactoring, completed\n\n- core/project/scribz-task-context-artifact-convention.md\n  Description: Task research artifacts should be stored under each task's context folder and indexed in context.md.\n  Tags: agents, convention, project, scribz, task-context, workflow\n\n- core/project/test-infrastructure.md\n  Description: Implementation of flexible, non-brittle test infrastructure for pi-memory-md\n  Tags: testing, vitest, infrastructure, completed\n\n- core/system/agent-memory-system-guide-additive-rollout-and-stage-gates-reduce-risk.md\n  Description: Rollout constraints and evidence gates that keep memory-system changes reversible and observable.\n  Tags: pkm, rollout, safeguards, staging\n\n- core/system/agent-memory-system-guide-durable-markdown-is-canonical-and-operational-layers-are-not.md\n  Description: Defines canonical-vs-operational memory boundaries so agents do not confuse retrieval layers with durable knowledge.\n  Tags: architecture, memory-operations, pi-memory-md, pkm\n\n- core/system/agent-memory-system-guide-retrieval-must-stay-layer-specific.md\n  Description: Tool-selection policy that prevents cross-layer leakage between markdown, recall, and archival stores.\n  Tags: memory-operations, pi-memory-md, retrieval, safeguards\n\n- core/system/agent-memory-system-guide-the-inbox-lifecycle-is-capture-triage-promote-archive.md\n  Description: Defines the required state machine for inbox handling, including provenance and promotion metadata constraints.\n  Tags: inbox, lifecycle, memory-operations, pkm\n\n- core/system/agent-memory-system-guide-wiki-linkable-claim-titles-keep-notes-reusable.md\n  Description: Naming contract for durable notes so files stay standalone, compos